500|$|One common {{technique}} is to memorize {{a story or}} poem in which the word lengths represent the digits of : The first word has three letters, the second word has one, the third has four, the fourth has one, the fifth has five, and so on. An early example of a memorization aid, originally devised by English scientist James Jeans, is [...] "How I <b>want</b> <b>a</b> <b>drink,</b> alcoholic of course, after the heavy lectures involving quantum mechanics." [...] When a poem is used, it is {{sometimes referred to as}} a piem. Poems for memorizing [...] have been composed in several languages in addition to English. [...] Record-setting [...] memorizers typically do not rely on poems, but instead use methods such as remembering number patterns and the method of loci.|$|E
